CERVIX, BIOPSY:   - Squamous cell carcinoma.  (JN/mg)    Dr. Shenoy has reviewed the slides and concurs      I certify the accuracy of this report on the basis of my personal observations and interpretation.  Microscopic examination performed on all specimens except gross only.  Specimen #1 is received in formalin in a container labeled with the patient's name, medical record number, "uterus" per the requisition and consists of an aggregate of tan white-pink irregularly-shaped tissue fragments (2.6 x 1.8 x 1.0 cm).  The specimen is serially sectioned and submitted entirely in biopsy bags in 1A - 1B.  (AA/mj)The sections show three fragments of atypical squamous epithelium that are admixed with abundant acute neutrophilic exudate and superficial squamous debris.  The intact fragments consist of proliferation of markedly atypical squamous non-keratinizing squamous epithelium.  The nuclei are large with abundant cytoplasm.  Atypical mitotic figures are frequently present.  In one fragment there is underlying stroma present and irregular fingers of atypical neoplastic squamous epithelium is seen extending into the stroma. A. CERVIX, LEEP:  - Low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL, CIN 1)  - Mild chronic cervicitis  - No high-grade dysplasia or transformation zone identified       I certify the accuracy of this report on the basis of my personal observations and interpretation.  Microscopic examination performed on all specimens except gross only.    The overall morphological findings show features consistent with cautery and reactive changes in block A2. The focus of cautery artifact is difficult to evaluate morphologically, so immunohistochemical stains (IHC; single antibody procedures with adequate controls) for Ki-67 and p16 were performed; the immunostain for p16 shows no block-like staining, and for Ki-67 shows no increase in mitotic activity (with mitoses largely confined to the basal layer of the squamous epithelium), confirming the morphological impression.  A. Cervix. 1. UTERUS, UTERUS AND TUBES, SUPRACERVICAL HYSTERECTOMY WITH BILATERAL SALPINGECTOMY:   - Uterus with exaggerated placental site   - Endometrium with decidual changes   - Unremarkable serosa   - Bilateral unremarkable fallopian tubes      I certify the accuracy of this report on the basis of my personal observations and interpretation.  Microscopic examination performed on all specimens except gross only.  Exaggerated placental sites have been associated with emergency hysterectomies and abortions.Specimen #1 is received in formalin labeled with the patient's name, medical record number, "uterus and tubes" and consists of a supracervical tan-pink uterine fundus (8.6 x 7.2 x 4.5 cm, 232 grams) with attached bilateral fimbriated fallopian tubes (right: 9.7 x 0.8 x 0.8 cm, left: 9.9 x 0.8 x 0.6 cm).  The uterine fundus serosal surface is tan-pink and smooth.  The cervical canal resection margin is markedly dilated (3.4 cm in diameter) with adhered clotted blood.  The cervical resection margin is inked blue and the uterine fundus is bivalved to reveal an endometrial cavity (6.5 x 4.0 cm) with a marked amount of adhered clotted blood and red-brown soft tissue ranging from 0.2 to 0.7 cm thick.  Both halves are serially sectioned to reveal a myometrium ranging from 1.5 to 2.0 cm with tightly adhered clotted blood and probable decidua.  The bilateral fallopian tubes are serially sectioned to reveal tan lumen.    Section code:  1A:  Anterior ectocervical canal resection margin  1B - 1D: Anterior endomyometrium  1E:  Posterior ectocervical canal resection margin  1F - 1H: Posterior endomyometrium  1I:  Right fallopian tube, representative  1J:  Left fallopian tube, representative    (AI/mg)The sections of uterus show endometrium with progestational changes.  In on area the walll of the uterus is infiltrated by intermediate trophoblasts and multinucleated trophoblasts.  The trophoblasts infiltrate between bundles of smooth muscle in cords, nest and individual cells up to 7 mm in depth.  The trophoblast react strongly to cytokeratin and weakly to HCG.Pre-op diagnosis:  Abortion with septic shock [O03.87, R65.21]  Hemorrhage [R58]  Unless specified otherwise above, the quality of the H&E and any other special stains performed at University of Mississippi Medical Center Pathology Laboratory (AFB, PAS, immunostains, etc) is satisfactory, and any internal or external positive and negative controls react appropriately. Additionally, and separately in the container is a tan-pink fimbriated fallopian tube (3.9 x 0.5 x 0.5 cm). The uterine fundus serosal surface is tan, smooth, markedly distorted, and disrupted in the anterior aspect. There are marked adhesions identified at the anterior and posterior aspects of the uterus. The ectocervix (3.4 x 3.3 cm) is tan-pink and slightly ragged. The specimen is bivalved to reveal an endocervical canal (3.9 cm in length) which is slightly hemorrhagic with herringbone architecture. The endometrial cavity (4.2 x 1.2 x 0.2 cm) is hemorrhagic and markedly distorted by a tan-white whorled nodule (5.6 x 4.9 x 4.0 cm) present at the fundus in the anterior aspect within tan-pink slightly trabeculated myometrium ranging from 2.2-3.2 cm in thickness. There is a transmural rupture (5.2 x 3.6 x 2.8 cm) identified at the anterior aspect of the uterus exposing the tan-white whorled nodule. Both anterior and posterior halves are serially sectioned to reveal the tan-white whorled nodule with white homogenous cut surfaces. The bilateral fallopian tubes are serially sectioned to reveal tan dilated lumens.
